01:03:45.070 --> 01:03:47.690
Gould has a music lesson.

01:03:47.690 --> 01:03:50.000
So I said, so you're
parting the drapes for me.

01:03:50.000 --> 01:03:52.320
He said, what?

01:03:52.320 --> 01:03:54.950
I said, you're parting
the drapes for me,

01:03:54.950 --> 01:03:56.850
so that I can get on stage?

01:03:56.850 --> 01:03:57.350
He said.

01:03:57.350 --> 01:03:59.329
I don't know about that.

01:03:59.329 --> 01:03:59.870
I said, What?

01:03:59.870 --> 01:04:00.750
Well, what are you doing here?

01:04:00.750 --> 01:04:02.000
He said, I don't know, Cleese.

01:04:02.000 --> 01:04:03.610
He just asked me to
stand in for him.

01:04:03.610 --> 01:04:07.490
So I could hear my cue coming
up in about 10 seconds.

01:04:07.490 --> 01:04:11.990
I start groping the
drapes in the dark,

01:04:11.990 --> 01:04:14.400
trying to find the gap
myself, desperately

01:04:14.400 --> 01:04:16.970
grabbing at the
pitch black cloth,

01:04:16.970 --> 01:04:19.810
in search of an opening
as the seconds tick away.

01:04:19.810 --> 01:04:21.250
And there's my cue.

01:04:21.250 --> 01:04:25.940
So I just walk forward
into the drapes

01:04:25.940 --> 01:04:31.110
and keep trudging onward against
the weight of all the velvet

01:04:31.110 --> 01:04:33.640
cloth that is clinging to me.

01:04:33.640 --> 01:04:36.030
And the audience start
to giggle at the sight

01:04:36.030 --> 01:04:42.560
of this strange, increasingly
large bulge in the back cloth,

01:04:42.560 --> 01:04:47.980
that is ever more slowly making
its way towards-- The actors

01:04:47.980 --> 01:04:50.080
step back in alarm.

01:04:50.080 --> 01:04:52.730
At least I'm
frightening someone.

01:04:52.730 --> 01:04:55.180
And I manage just
to keep moving,

01:04:55.180 --> 01:04:58.130
so that when I have reached
a point about halfway

01:04:58.130 --> 01:05:02.880
to the front of the stalls, the
drapes now at full extension,

01:05:02.880 --> 01:05:07.220
start sliding back over my
head and finally fall away

01:05:07.220 --> 01:05:10.630
from me, revealing a
strange creature, a lackard,

01:05:10.630 --> 01:05:15.010
stick insect, apparently in
a fright wig, who announces,

01:05:15.010 --> 01:05:18.920
(DEEP GRAVELLY
VOICE) I am Lucifer.

01:05:18.920 --> 01:05:20.750
By which time most
of the audience

01:05:20.750 --> 01:05:24.490
had lost contact
with their chairs.

01:05:24.490 --> 01:05:25.645
That was my first attempt.

01:05:28.570 --> 01:05:32.470
And then the next time I did it
was 34 years later for Kenneth

01:05:32.470 --> 01:05:36.326
Branagh, when I was in
Mary Shelley's Frankenstein

01:05:36.326 --> 01:05:42.520
and I played Kenneth Branagh's
anatomy tutor, Dr. Waldman,

01:05:42.520 --> 01:05:45.410
and managed to play the
whole thing without getting

01:05:45.410 --> 01:05:50.030
a single laugh, not even when
Robert De Niro stabbed me

01:05:50.030 --> 01:05:51.520
to death.

01:05:51.520 --> 01:05:53.380
So that was a considerable
accomplishment.

01:05:57.240 --> 01:05:59.619
AUDIENCE: So you talked a lot
about the creative process,

01:05:59.619 --> 01:06:01.160
which was really
interesting to hear,

01:06:01.160 --> 01:06:04.650
because I haven't actually heard
you talk about that before.

01:06:04.650 --> 01:06:06.520
What changes with that?

01:06:06.520 --> 01:06:08.810
You talked a lot
about the unconscious

01:06:08.810 --> 01:06:12.020
and how important
that is to creativity.

01:06:12.020 --> 01:06:14.960
What changes when you're doing
something collaboratively

01:06:14.960 --> 01:06:15.752
with somebody else?

01:06:15.752 --> 01:06:17.376
JOHN CLEESE: Well,
first of all, you've

01:06:17.376 --> 01:06:18.850
got to be very
relaxed with them.

01:06:18.850 --> 01:06:20.350
When you start
writing with someone,

01:06:20.350 --> 01:06:24.170
it's just a tiny little bit like
a sort of platonic first date.

01:06:24.170 --> 01:06:26.390
Because you've got
get to know each other

01:06:26.390 --> 01:06:27.352
and trust each other.

01:06:27.352 --> 01:06:28.310
Do you see what I mean?

01:06:28.310 --> 01:06:30.680
Because you have to,
to really be creative,

01:06:30.680 --> 01:06:33.660
you have to say the first thing
that comes into your mind.

01:06:33.660 --> 01:06:36.190
You mustn't process it
with the critical mind

01:06:36.190 --> 01:06:37.770
before you voice it.

01:06:37.770 --> 01:06:40.510
You've just got to say
what comes into your mind.

01:06:40.510 --> 01:06:43.080
And that means you have to
have a certain amount of trust

01:06:43.080 --> 01:06:44.800
in the person you're
with so he won't

01:06:44.800 --> 01:06:46.320
think you're a complete prat.

01:06:46.320 --> 01:06:49.030
Or she won't think you're
a complete prat if you

01:06:49.030 --> 01:06:52.150
say something that is silly or
dumb or something like that.

01:06:52.150 --> 01:06:53.640
So there's a
process in which you

01:06:53.640 --> 01:06:57.060
have to get very, very
comfortable with someone.

01:06:57.060 --> 01:06:58.770
Once you've done
that, what happens

01:06:58.770 --> 01:07:02.350
is that the ideas
build off each other.

01:07:02.350 --> 01:07:05.170
You sort of bat things
backwards and forwards.

01:07:05.170 --> 01:07:07.950
And they move forward
so fast that you

01:07:07.950 --> 01:07:10.670
can't see the
process at the time.

01:07:10.670 --> 01:07:14.200
But all you do is, when you
do get to the good idea,

01:07:14.200 --> 01:07:16.320
after batting it
backwards and forwards,

01:07:16.320 --> 01:07:19.380
you can never really
remember how you got there.

01:07:19.380 --> 01:07:20.530
Do you see what I mean?

01:07:20.530 --> 01:07:21.530
Only it doesn't matter.

01:07:21.530 --> 01:07:22.470
It doesn't matter.

01:07:22.470 --> 01:07:24.830
You literally don't
know who said what,

01:07:24.830 --> 01:07:26.880
but you know that you've
got to this thing.

01:07:26.880 --> 01:07:30.860
And it's because you've got two
minds batting off each other.

01:07:30.860 --> 01:07:32.830
So you get somewhere
that I think

01:07:32.830 --> 01:07:34.465
you wouldn't get on your own.

01:07:34.465 --> 01:07:37.170
Now, obviously you can't do
that with an autobiography,

01:07:37.170 --> 01:07:39.240
because it's so highly personal.

01:07:39.240 --> 01:07:41.550
Now, if you're writing
a play, in which there's

01:07:41.550 --> 01:07:44.060
some particular thing
you want to say,

01:07:44.060 --> 01:07:46.850
well, you shouldn't write
that with somebody else

01:07:46.850 --> 01:07:49.540
unless they have exactly
the same views as you.

01:07:49.540 --> 01:07:50.970
Do you see what I mean?

01:07:50.970 --> 01:07:55.470
You should just-- I think
that thing that sums it up.

01:07:55.470 --> 01:07:58.044
You get to a place you'd
never get on our own.

01:07:58.044 --> 01:07:59.960
That's the advantage of
collaborative writing.

01:07:59.960 --> 01:08:03.245
But I have to say, you have
to keep the group very small.

01:08:03.245 --> 01:08:06.520
If you try and get four people
writing creatively together,

01:08:06.520 --> 01:08:08.320
you get nothing done at all.

01:08:08.320 --> 01:08:11.320
Because always one of
the four will disagree.

01:08:11.320 --> 01:08:13.770
When there's three, you could
get a certain amount done,

01:08:13.770 --> 01:08:15.020
but it's a slower process.

01:08:15.020 --> 01:08:17.450
So I think really
two is the best.

01:08:17.450 --> 01:08:18.910
And what used to
happen in Python,

01:08:18.910 --> 01:08:21.600
we worked in twos
and ones, and then we

01:08:21.600 --> 01:08:23.870
would get together
every six or seven days

01:08:23.870 --> 01:08:27.100
and read out what we'd written.

01:08:27.100 --> 01:08:29.640
And then we would simply see
whether we laughed or not.

01:08:29.640 --> 01:08:31.020
I mean it was very simple.

01:08:31.020 --> 01:08:33.350
If we all thought it was
funny, we all laughed,

01:08:33.350 --> 01:08:34.770
it was in the show.

01:08:34.770 --> 01:08:37.314
And if not, we would send
it off to some other show.

01:08:40.131 --> 01:08:41.380
AUDIENCE: Thank you very much.

01:08:41.380 --> 01:08:42.700
JOHN CLEESE: OK.

01:08:42.700 --> 01:08:43.760
Yes.

01:08:43.760 --> 01:08:44.260
Hello.

01:08:44.260 --> 01:08:45.968
AUDIENCE: A few years
ago, I found myself

01:08:45.968 --> 01:08:47.350
at the Globe Theatre in London.

01:08:47.350 --> 01:08:49.100
And I was standing on
a paving stone that

01:08:49.100 --> 01:08:52.069
said Michael Palin
spelled incorrectly.

01:08:52.069 --> 01:08:55.290
And next to it was one with
your name, spelled correctly.

01:08:55.290 --> 01:08:57.552
JOHN CLEESE: Say that,
one was Michael Palin

01:08:57.552 --> 01:08:58.819
AUDIENCE: Pallen.

01:08:58.819 --> 01:09:01.210
JOHN CLEESE: Palin,
you must say Palin.

01:09:01.210 --> 01:09:02.710
He doesn't like
being called Pallen.

01:09:02.710 --> 01:09:04.390
AUDIENCE: But it
was spelled Pallen.

01:09:04.390 --> 01:09:05.640
JOHN CLEESE: Oh, that's right.

01:09:05.640 --> 01:09:06.229
OK.

01:09:06.229 --> 01:09:06.450
That's right.

01:09:06.450 --> 01:09:06.949
Yes.

01:09:06.949 --> 01:09:08.819
You're absolutely right.

01:09:08.819 --> 01:09:09.770
Oh, my god.

01:09:09.770 --> 01:09:11.359
You're way ahead of me.

01:09:11.359 --> 01:09:12.200
That's right.

01:09:12.200 --> 01:09:15.859
Michael doesn't like
being called Pallen.

01:09:15.859 --> 01:09:27.529
So I paid-- I paid to have
one of those stones put

01:09:27.529 --> 01:09:28.540
in with a double L.

01:09:28.540 --> 01:09:33.620
Oh, the worst thing I ever did
was, at the Hampstead Theater,

01:09:33.620 --> 01:09:37.950
when they were asking people who
went regularly, to put up money

01:09:37.950 --> 01:09:41.210
to buy seats in
people's names, right?

01:09:41.210 --> 01:09:44.899
And I bought one of the
name of Martin Bormann.

01:09:44.899 --> 01:09:52.390
Now, he was part of Hitler's
very tight group of associates.

01:09:52.390 --> 01:09:53.910
And nobody spotted it.

01:09:58.140 --> 01:10:00.480
AUDIENCE: I was wondering
if Michael Palin knows

01:10:00.480 --> 01:10:02.390
about that stone at the Globe.

01:10:02.390 --> 01:10:04.590
And if you know, what
his reaction was?

01:10:04.590 --> 01:10:08.580
JOHN CLEESE: You know,
I'm not absolutely sure.

01:10:08.580 --> 01:10:09.510
I will ask him.

01:10:09.510 --> 01:10:11.300
But I'll tell you
a story about Palin

01:10:11.300 --> 01:10:14.590
because he and I played jokes
on each other all the time.

01:10:14.590 --> 01:10:18.260
And on one occasion,
somebody came to me and said,

01:10:18.260 --> 01:10:23.680
would you and Michael like
to do some program together?

01:10:23.680 --> 01:10:25.390
And I thought that would be fun.

01:10:25.390 --> 01:10:27.140
So I thought how do I
get hold of Michael?

01:10:27.140 --> 01:10:28.990
So I called his home.

01:10:28.990 --> 01:10:30.130
And Helen answered.

01:10:30.130 --> 01:10:34.990
And of course, he was off making
one of those, [YAWN] sorry,

01:10:34.990 --> 01:10:36.750
one of those travel
programs of his.

01:10:41.240 --> 01:10:44.820
And Helen said, he's at
this hotel in Helsinki.

01:10:44.820 --> 01:10:48.910
So I thought well, I'll give
him a call this evening when

01:10:48.910 --> 01:10:49.910
he's finished shooting.

01:10:49.910 --> 01:10:52.380
And I called him
and asked for him.

01:10:52.380 --> 01:10:55.880
I said, can I speak
to Mr. Palin, please.

01:10:55.880 --> 01:10:58.650
And there was the usual delay
while they put me through.

01:10:58.650 --> 01:11:01.220
And while I was waiting,
I thought to myself,

01:11:01.220 --> 01:11:04.420
he doesn't know who this is.

01:11:04.420 --> 01:11:07.230
Then I thought, he
doesn't know where I am.

01:11:07.230 --> 01:11:09.020
So when he answered
the phone, and said,

01:11:09.020 --> 01:11:11.228
hello, I said, (IN A NORWEGIAN
ACCENT) Ah, Mr. Palin,

01:11:11.228 --> 01:11:15.110
my name is Larsley Bristom,
I'm a television producer

01:11:15.110 --> 01:11:18.220
with NRK television in Oslo.

01:11:18.220 --> 01:11:23.270
And were wondering if you might
just do an interview with us.

01:11:23.270 --> 01:11:25.765
And he said, I'm awfully sorry
because I'm going to bed now

01:11:25.765 --> 01:11:27.300
and I'm off early
in the morning.

01:11:27.300 --> 01:11:31.250
And I said, no, Mr. Palin,
not an interview tomorrow,

01:11:31.250 --> 01:11:33.200
but an interview now.

01:11:33.200 --> 01:11:34.200
He said, now?

01:11:34.200 --> 01:11:38.290
I said, yes, I'm downstairs
in the lobby of your hotel

01:11:38.290 --> 01:11:40.040
with a film crew.

01:11:40.040 --> 01:11:43.600
And we have the chairs set
up and the lighting is ready.

01:11:43.600 --> 01:11:46.252
Could you come down?

01:11:46.252 --> 01:11:50.150
And he said, I'm
already in my pajamas.

01:11:50.150 --> 01:11:52.800
And I said, Oh, the
Norwegians would

01:11:52.800 --> 01:11:55.990
think that was
very witty, if you

01:11:55.990 --> 01:11:59.810
do the interview in
your pajamas, Mr. Palin.

01:11:59.810 --> 01:12:02.650
That would be really funny.

01:12:02.650 --> 01:12:07.790
He started to get quite ratty,
which Michael very seldom does.

01:12:07.790 --> 01:12:08.910
So I kept going.

01:12:08.910 --> 01:12:12.412
I said, but it's so important
that we interview you.

01:12:12.412 --> 01:12:14.120
And he said, well why
is it so important.

01:12:14.120 --> 01:12:17.910
I said, because we're doing
it to tribute to the greatest

01:12:17.910 --> 01:12:20.110
comedian in the world,
Mr. John Cleese.

01:12:27.850 --> 01:12:33.595
And it's very important that
we speak to one of his helpers.

01:12:48.778 --> 01:12:50.580
He began getting really cross.

01:12:50.580 --> 01:12:54.790
And I said, Michael, it's me.

01:12:54.790 --> 01:12:57.300
And I swear, he laughed
for two minutes.

01:12:57.300 --> 01:12:58.150
I mean, he just--

01:13:05.685 --> 01:13:06.310
We've finished.

01:13:06.310 --> 01:13:07.393
JESSE NICHOLS: I think so.

01:13:07.393 --> 01:13:08.630
I think that wraps it up.

01:13:08.630 --> 01:13:10.927
JOHN CLEESE: Are you all happy?

01:13:10.927 --> 01:13:11.905
[APPLAUSE]

01:13:11.905 --> 01:13:12.883
JOHN CLEESE: Thank you.

01:13:16.800 --> 01:13:18.730
Oh, incidentally,
any of you who've

01:13:18.730 --> 01:13:21.840
been nice enough
to buy a book, I

01:13:21.840 --> 01:13:24.130
will be very happy to
sign that, if you'd

01:13:24.130 --> 01:13:26.470
like to bring it up to me now.

01:13:26.470 --> 01:13:29.750
OK, I'll put your
name and my signature,

01:13:29.750 --> 01:13:32.082
unless you want someone
else's like Michael's.

01:13:32.082 --> 01:13:34.040
JESSE NICHOLS: Thank you
everyone, for joining.

01:13:34.040 --> 01:13:37.690
And John Cleese.

